  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the Cherethites and the Pelethites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The former of these names is found ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 30:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as the name of a people to the south of the Philistines. Hence it has been held by some that the second name, Pelethites, must also be of the same character, and that probably it is connected with the word ‘Philistine.’ It seems not impossible that David from his early residence in the country of the Philistines may have attached a body of men to him from among those peoples and constituted them his first body-guard (Josephus calls them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "σωματοφύλακες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which while retaining their old title would after the king’s accession be recruited from any of his most trusty supporters. We need not suppose therefore that though called by the old name they were largely composed of aliens. The older interpretations, connecting the words with Hebrew verbs, have been ‘executioners and runners’; and the Targum interprets them as ‘archers and slingers’ and in one place as ‘nobles and common soldiers.’ They are clearly to be identified with ‘the mighty men’ mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as not being with Adonijah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 38.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "So Zadok the priest, and Nathan the prophet, and Benaiah the son of Jehoiada, and the Cherethites, and the Pelethites",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [these were the royal bodyguard - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "Σωματοφύλακες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Josephus calls them - who were commanded by Benaiah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 15:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 20:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 23:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But while their functions are pretty well understood, great difference of opinion exists as to the origin or meaning of the words. By some they are supposed to be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Gentile",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " names. A tribe of Cherethites is mentioned ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 30:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". (Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 25:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Zephaniah 2:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and in close connexion with the Philistines (ver. 16). Hence Cherethite has been thought to be another name for Philistine; and as the LXX. and Syr. render the word \"Cretans,\" it has been conjectured that the Philistines had their origin from Crete. They did come from Caphtor, and that is probably Crete (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 10:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 47:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 9:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פְּלֵתִי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " again, is not unlike ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פְּלִשְּׁתִי",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In favor of this view is the fact that David certainly had a bodyguard of foreign mercenaries (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 15:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the \"Gittites\" are connected with the Cherethites). Nor does it make against it that \"two designations\" would thus \"be employed side by side for one and the same people\" - as if we should speak of Britons and Englishmen (Bahr). For the names look like a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "paronomasia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - of which the Jews were very fond - and a trick of this kind would at once account for the tautology. [Since writing this, I find the same idea has already occurred to Ewald.] But the other view, adopted by Gesenius, is that the names are names of office and function. Cherethite he would derive from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "תָרַכ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cut, slay; and by Cherethites he would understand \"executioners,\" which the royal bodyguard were in ancient despotisms (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 39:1, Hebrews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Daniel 2:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. See on 1 Kings 2:25). In the Pelethites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "פֶּלֶת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", swiftness) he would see the public couriers (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἄγγαροι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of Eastern men. archies (see Herod. 8:98 and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 30:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). We see the guard discharging the function first named in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 10:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:4, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and the latter in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (marg.)] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "went down",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from the palace on Mount Zion] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and caused Solomon to ride upon King David's mule, and brought him to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עַל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": cf. 2:26] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Gihon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Chald., Syr., Arab., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Shiloha",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "]. 1 Kings 1:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The anointing of Solomon was carried out immediately, as the king had commanded. On the Crethi and Plethi see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"The oil-horn out of the tent\" (i.e., a vessel made of horn and containing oil) was no doubt one which held the holy anointing oil, with which the priests and the vessels of the sanctuary were anointed (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 30:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".). The tent (האהל), however, is not the tabernacle at Gibeon, but the tent set up by David for the ark of the covenant upon Mount Zion (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 6:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). For even though Zadok was appointed high priest at the tabernacle at Gibeon, and Abiathar, who held with Adonijah, at the ark of the covenant, the two high priests were not so unfriendly towards one another, that Zadok could not have obtained admission to the ark of the covenant in Abiathar's absence to fetch away the anointing oil. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]